{{Infobox person | name = Aaron Hicklin | image = | alt = | caption = | birth_name = | birth_date = <!-- {{birth date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} for living people. For people who have died, use {{Birth date|YYYY|MM|DD}}. --> | birth_place = [[Wiltshire]], [[England]], United Kingdom<ref name=TG/> | death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) --> | death_place = | alma_mater = [[St John's Marlborough]] | nationality = | other_names = | occupation = Editor, [[columnist]], author, writer | years_active = | known_for = | notable_works = }}
'''Aaron Hicklin''' is the editor-in-chief of ''[[Out (magazine)|Out]]'', a United States [[LGBT]] magazine.<ref name=TG>Andrew Clark, [http://media.guardian.co.uk/mediaguardian/story/0,,2057733,00.html "Andrew Clark meets Aaron Hicklin"], ''The Guardian'' profile of Aaron Hicklin, 16 April 2007, MediaGuardian section, p5</ref><ref>[http://www.politico.com/media/story/2012/04/out-lays-off-its-entire-editorial-staff-but-editor-aaron-hicklin-wants-to-hire-most-back-into-his-new-startup-000418 Politico]</ref><ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2015/12/07/t-magazine/one-grand-bookstore-aaron-hicklin-profile.html?_r=0 The New York Times]</ref>
Previously, he was editor of ''[[BlackBook Magazine|BlackBook]]'' magazine. He began his tenure as editor-in-chief of ''Out'' in April 2006 after Brendon Lemon resigned in October 2005. Before this he also had a column in the [[Scotland|Scottish]] newspaper, ''[[The Sunday Herald]]'', in which he wrote articles about life in New York. He is the author of ''Boy Soldiers'' (Mainstream), and the editor of ''The Revolution Will Be Accessorized'' (Harper Perennial), an anthology of essays that appeared in ''BlackBook''.
