In [[linguistics]], '''coercion''' is a term applied to a process of reinterpretation that is triggered by a mismatch between the [[semantics|semantic]] properties of a selector and the [[semantics|semantic]] properties of the selected element.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Lauwers|first1=P.|last2=Willems|first2=D.|title=Coercion: Definition and challenges, current approaches, and new trends|journal=Linguistics|date=2011|volume=49|issue=6|pages=1219–1235|url=http://www.degruyter.com/view/j/ling.2011.49.issue-6/ling.2011.034/ling.2011.034.xml?format=INT|accessdate=11 January 2015|doi=10.1515/ling.2011.034}}</ref>  The term was first used in the semantic literature by Marc Moens and [[Mark Steedman]], who adopted it on "loose analogy with type-coercion in programming languages".<ref>{{cite journal|author1=Marc Moens|author2=Mark Steedman|title=Temporal Ontology and Temporal Reference|journal=Computational Linguistics|date=1988|volume=14|issue=2|pages=15–28}}</ref> In the framework of the generative lexicon (a formal compositional approach to lexical semantics), Pustejovsky (1995:111) defines coercion as "a semantic operation that converts an argument to the type which is expected by a function, where it would otherwise result in a type error." "Coercion" in the Pustejovsky framework includes complement coercion and aspectual coercion.<ref name=Pust1995>{{cite book|last1=Pustejovsky|first1=James|title=The Generative Lexicon|date=1995|publisher=The MIT Press|location=Cambridge, MA}}</ref>

An example of complement coercion is the sentence "I began the book", where the predicate "began" is assumed to be a selector which requires its complement to denote an event, but "a book" denotes an entity, not an event. So, on the coercion analysis, "begin" coerces "a book" from an entity to an event involving that entity, allowing the sentence to be interpreted to mean, e.g., "I began to read a book," or "I began to write a book." <ref name=Pust1995/>

An example of aspectual coercion involving temporal connectives is "Let's leave after dessert" (Pustejovsky 1995:230). Another example of aspectual coercion from psycholinguistics research includes sentences such as "The tiger jumped for an hour," where the prepositional phrase "for an hour" coerces the lexical meaning of "jump" to be iterative across the entire duration.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Piñango |first1=Maria |last2=Winnick |first2=Aaron |last3=Zurif |first3=Edgar |last4=Ullah |first4=Rashad |date=2006 |title=The Time Course of Semantic Composition: The Case of Aspectual Coercion |url=https://link.springer.com/article/10.1007%2Fs10936-006-9013-z?LI=true |journal=Journal of Psycholinguistic Research |volume=35 |issue=3 |pages=233–244 |doi= 10.1007/s10936-006-9013-z |access-date= July 18, 2017 }}</ref>

Coercion is closely related to the notions of active zone, [[construal]]/[[conceptualization]], and [[syntactic]] [[Communication accommodation theory|accommodation]] known from various schools within the [[cognitive linguistics]] movement.

