'''Dr. John L. Steckley''' is a [[Canadians|Canadian]] scholar specializing in [[Native American studies]] and the [[indigenous languages of the Americas]]. Steckley has a Ph.D. in education from the [[University of Toronto]]. He taught at [[Humber College]] in [[Toronto|Toronto, Ontario]], from 1983 until his retirement in June 2015.
Steckley is reportedly the last known speaker of the [[Wyandot language|Wyandot (or Huron) language]], which he has studied for over thirty years.<ref name=star/> He is also interested in place names as derived from indigenous languages, and aims to correct common misconceptions regarding their original derivations.<ref>[http://www.usitt.org/sightlines/v44/n07/stories/Toronto.html How Toronto Got Its Names] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080720102358/http://www.usitt.org/sightlines/v44/n07/stories/Toronto.html |date=20 July 2008 }}, Sightlines, August 2004 Volume XLIV, Number 7 ([[United States Institute for Theatre Technology]], August 2004)</ref>
Steckley has become a deeply respected figure amongst the Wyandot. On his adoption into the Wyandot tribe in 1999, he was named ''Tehaondechoren'' ("he who splits the country in two").<ref name=reist>Reist, Michael, ''[http://www.northpeelmediagroup.com/sideroads/caledon/articleV2.php?columnId=250&readArticle=bf65291e31fb7a379d0109a0e03023f4&ArtSection=features&ArtType=article Member of the tribe: Meet Boltonite John Steckley, author and honorary member of the Huron Tribe] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100515165031/http://www.northpeelmediagroup.com/sideroads/caledon/articleV2.php?columnId=250&readArticle=bf65291e31fb7a379d0109a0e03023f4&ArtSection=features&ArtType=article |date=15 May 2010 }}'', ''The Caledon Enterprise & Erin Advocate'', 28 January 2008</ref> He was also given the name "Hechon" by descendants of the Huron in [[Loretteville, Quebec City]], while teaching them their own historical language.<ref name=reist/> This was a name that had previously been given to [[Jean de Brébeuf]] (1593–1649), one of the [[North American Martyrs]], by his Huron and Wyandot followers.<ref name=reist/><ref>{{CathEncy|wstitle=Huron Indians}}</ref>
His 2007 ''Huron-English Dictionary'' was the first book of its type for over 250 years to be published.<ref name=star/><ref>Steckley, John, ''A Huron-English / English-Huron Dictionary, Listing Both Nouns and Verb Roots'' (Mellen, 2007) {{ISBN|0-7734-5258-3}}</ref>
In 2007, [[Laval University]] received a federal grant of $1 million for development of its Huron-language teaching materials in collaboration with Steckley.<ref name=star>J. Goddard, [https://www.thestar.com/News/Ontario/article/288382 Scholar sole speaker of Huron language], [[Toronto Star]], Dec 24, 2007.</ref>
Steckley has written widely on a variety of sociological and anthropological topics, including a recent book on [[gibbon]]s.<ref>{{Cite book|title = Gibbons: The Invisible Apes|url = https://www.amazon.com/Gibbons-Invisible-Apes-John-Steckley/dp/1772440078|publisher = Rock's Mills Press|date = 2015-06-09|isbn = 9781772440072|language = English|first = John|last = Steckley}}</ref>
== Bibliography == * ''Full Circle: Canada's First Nations'' (2001) * ''Aboriginal Voices and the Politics of Representation in Canadian Introductory Sociology Textbooks'' (2003) * ''A Huron-English / English-Huron Dictionary, Listing Both Nouns and Verb Roots'' (2007) * ''Elements of Sociology: A Critical Canadian Introduction'' (with Guy Letts) (2008) * ''Beyond Their Years: Five Native Women's Stories'' (2011) * ''Learning from the Past: Five Cases of Aboriginal Justice'' (2013) * ''Foundations of Sociology'' (2014) * ''[https://www.amazon.com/Eighteenth-Century-Wyandot-Clan-Based-Indigenous-Studies/dp/1554589568 The Eighteenth-Century Wyandot: A Clan-Based Study]'' (2014) * ''[https://www.amazon.com/Gibbons-Invisible-Apes-John-Steckley/dp/1772440078 Gibbons: The Invisible Apes]'' (2015)
