{{distinguish|Limassa language}} {{Infobox language |name=Massa |nativename=Masana |states=[[Chad]], [[Cameroon]] |speakers=230,000 |date=1982–2006 |ref = e18 |familycolor=Afro-Asiatic |fam2=[[Chadic languages|Chadic]] |fam3=[[Masa languages|Masa]] |fam4=North |iso3=mcn |glotto=masa1322 |glottoname=Manasa |glotto2=gize1234 |glottoname2=Gizey |glotto3=hama1241 |glottoname3=Ham }}
'''Massa''' (or '''Masana''', '''Masa''') is a [[Chadic language]] spoken in southern [[Chad]] and northern [[Cameroon]] by the [[Masa people]]. It has approximately 200,000 speakers.
Dialects are Bongor, Bugudum (Budugum), Domo, Gizay, Gumay, Ham, Walia, Wina (Viri), Yagwa.
[[Kim language|Kim]], a neighbouring language, was once misclassified as Masa.
